vels of physical, spiritual, and intellectual talent. In doing so, he affirms the notion that all of these slaves were unique individuals, despite the efforts of their owners and the wider Atlantic world to dehumanize and erase them. Biographical Dictionary of Enslaved Black People in the Maritimes helps us understand the challenges of race in our own time by telling a new story about Canadian history – one rooted in the difficulties of slavery and the actions taken to fight for dignity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aSlaveryzMaritime Provinces. 0aSlaveszMaritime ProvincesvBiographyvDictionaries. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAfrican American history.  aAtlantic world.  aBlack Canadian history.  aBritish North American history.  aCarolinas.  aChesapeake.  aMaritimes.  aUnited States history.  aWest Indies.  abiography.  aenslaved.  aslavery.  aslaves.1 aWright, Donald.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754384640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487543846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487543846/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK